input_text:
Intern: John A. Peterson Advisor: Dr. Michael Andersson
Institution: Department of Physics, University of Copenhagen

Abstract

Low-temperature physics, or cryogenics, is a field of physics that explores the behavior of materials at temperatures approaching absolute zero. This report presents an internship study focusing on the experimental investigation of superconductivity and quantum fluids at cryogenic temperatures. Using liquid helium-based cooling techniques, we examined the superconducting transition temperature of niobium samples and performed measurements on superfluid helium. Our study provides insights into the fundamental properties of quantum materials at ultra-low temperatures and highlights challenges in experimental cryogenics.

ontology_addendum.title: Cryogenic Physics Ontology
ontology_addendum.description: The Cryogenic Physics Ontology (CPO) provides a structured representation of concepts and relationships in the field of low-temperature physics, particularly focusing on superconductivity and quantum fluids. It aims to facilitate knowledge sharing and interoperability among researchers and institutions involved in cryogenic studies. The ontology encompasses entities related to materials, experimental techniques, and fundamental properties observed at ultra-low temperatures.
